<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Air France free to buy stake in Sabena
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL and PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission yesterday cleared Air France, the French state
airline, to take a 37.6 per cent stake in Sabena, its Belgian counterpart,
provided that rival carriers are allowed to compete on certain monopoly or
near-monopoly routes.
The decision ends almost a year of delays for the companies, which announced
they were ready to do a deal last September and signed an accord in April.
It also lets the two airlines forge a cross-border partnership to strengthen
their position in the European and world markets.
Air France said the compromise was 'a balanced agreement'.
The EC's merger control task force agreed terms for approval of the deal
within a month - but that followed many weeks of tough negotiation about the
legal basis for examining the deal and the anti-trust pledges made by the
airlines and their governments.
The pledges include:
One of the two companies will have to withdraw from the Brussels-Nice and
Brussels-Lyons routes to allow at least one rival airline into the market
Rival EC carriers will be allowed to compete with the planned Air
France-Sabena Brussels-to-Paris shuttle service Certain take-off and landing
slots will be kept available for rival airlines at Brussels airport
Air France and Sabena will have to abandon certain flights to Africa, if a
competing airline will take on the routes.
The Commission said it was 'very likely' that rival airlines would take up
the available slots and routes.
The EC has been worried by growing consolidation in the European airline
industry, which risks undermining the Commission's promotion of competition
through 'open skies'.
Last year the Commission told Air France to sell its 35 per cent stake in
the French regional carrier TAT after it took over UTA, the French long-haul
carrier, and Air Inter, the French domestic airline. British Airways agreed
last month to buy a 49 per cent stake in TAT to challenge Air France on its
home ground.
The loss-making Sabena said the Air France deal would help put it back on a
firm financial footing. Air France and its Belgian financial partners have
injected BFr6bn (Pounds 115m) of fresh capital in exchange for the stake.
</TEXT>
