<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Observer: Interlude
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Picture the scene. A party of wealthy corporate sponsors was invited to pop
into the Royal Opera House in Covent Garden last week to 'take a sniff at
work in progress'.
But the event lost some of its spontaneity when the orchestra, rehearsing
Porgy and Bess, downed tools.
An official plays down the incident saying it was all a misunderstanding.
The visit had been cleared with the orchestra representative so long ago
that 'it had slipped a few minds'. After the 'temporary communications blip'
had been sorted out the rehearsal went ahead.
However, at least one hard-nosed City type present was unimpressed and says
that the event is yet another sign that the Opera House 'has failed to come
to terms with basic management issues and is squandering its money'.
</TEXT>
