<TEXT>
The second half of tonight's double-bill of C4's arts programme Without
Walls is 'And God Created Tenors', an analysis of the sex appeal of tenors
from Caruso and Mario Lanza to Josef Locke, the Irish tenor whose reputation
has bloomed again thanks to the gruesomely whimsical film, 'Hear My Song'.
Civvies (BBC 1: 9.30), the series about ex-paras maladroitly readjusting to
civilian life, has more than an echo of John Macnab about it this week. Can
a bracing Highlands location rescue this disappointing drama from a
pedestrian script and its pervasive reek of sentimentality? Meanwhile BBC2
tells real tales from the front line in Battle Cries (9.50), part of the
current season about warfare.
Once there was a scheme to put a garden designed by Marx on top of the
Hayward Gallery. Tonight's Omnibus on BBC 1 (10.25) shows what we have
missed in 'The Lost Paradise - The Gardens of Roberto Burle Marx', an
uncritical presentation of the work of this undeniably important if
tiresomely vainglorious Brazilian landscape architect.
