FT  06 OCT 92 / Industry defends use of orimulsion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE orimulsion industry yesterday hit back at suggestions that it was a
'dirty fuel', after last week's statement by the pollution inspector-ate
that tougher environ-mental controls may be needed.
Mr Manuel de Oliveira, the chief executive of BP Bitor, the BP-Venezuelan
joint venture which is seeking to import orimulsion into the UK to be burnt
by power stations, said: 'It is a fact that all present and proposed uses of
orimulsion comply in every respect with current health, safety and
environmental legislation.'
He emphasised that orimulsion, a bitumen-based fuel, has a better
environmental performance than coal.
Last week, the Inspectorate of Pollution agreed to a delay in an application
by National Power to burn orimulsion at power stations in Pembroke and
Padiham, Lancs, saying it would require more environmental safeguards than
were being proposed.
'We shall do whatever we can to assist that process,' Mr de Oliveira said.
He warned that there could be no justi-fication for discriminatory action
against one energy resource.
