<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Nuclear safety levels set
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAFETY standards at future nuclear power stations should be set so that the
risk to the public is 10 times smaller than the danger of a road accident,
according to new guidelines published yesterday by the Health and Safety
Executive, the industrial safety regulator.
The HSE's report is a response to the 1986 public inquiry into the Sizewell
B nuclear reactor, which called for standards on the tolerable level of risk
to the public from nuclear power.
The HSE concludes: 'We propose to adopt a risk (of death to a member of the
public) of 1 in 100,000 a year as the benchmark for new nuclear power
stations in the UK'. It compares that with the risk of 1 in 10,000 of dying
in a traffic accident, 1 in 13,000 of a woman dying in childbirth, or 1 in
1,000,000 of dying in a fire or gas explosion at home.
The report differs from the HSE's preliminary 1988 study in that human error
is brought into the models, increasing some of the estimates of risk.
The HSE's consultation document applies only to future nuclear power
stations. Mr John Rimington, the HSE's director-general, said: 'We do not
know how to quantify the risk from the Magnox stations' - the oldest of
Britain's reactors. He added: 'What we do know is that they are enormously
robust.'
The HSE intends its recommendations to be part of the debate about the
future of Britain's nuclear power industry. However, no new nuclear power
stations are likely to be built until the completion of the government study
into nuclear power's future, due in 1994.
Tolerability of Risk from Nuclear Power Stations, HSE. HMSO. Pounds 12.
</TEXT>
