<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Vocational study sees maths gap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOCATIONAL qualifications should be strengthened in their mathematics
component, according to a study that compares the UK with France.
The study, published by the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research, concludes that maths teaching in France was more successful partly
because all vocational students studied a core mathematics curriculum of a
consistent standard.
In the UK, there was no core curriculum of mathematics and the new
employer-led vocational qualifications provided little incentive for its
teaching.
The author of the study, Mrs Alison Wolf, senior research officer and
research lecturer at the Institute of Education at the University of London,
said: 'This neglect of a core subject area hinders progression within the
qualifications system, depresses attainment and lowers aspirations of both
teachers and students.'
The study recommends specifying mathematical skills and formal examination
of mathematics in vocational courses.
National Institute Discussion Paper Number 23. NIESR, 2 Dean Trench Street,
Smith Square, London SW1P 3HE. Pounds 3.
</TEXT>
