FT  06 OCT 92 / Building chief condemns Lamont's 'lack of action'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION leaders yesterday condemned the government for failing to help
the recession-wracked industry.
Sir Brian Hill, president of the Building Employers Confederation, said he
had tried to explain the severity of the recession to Mr John Major, the
prime minister, and to Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, but that 'so far
there has been no real response in terms of government action'.
Sir Brian also highlighted job losses in the industry. He said jobs had been
shed at the rate of 580 for each working day for three years.
He added that 400,000 jobs had been lost during the past three years. A
further 50,000 jobs were like to disappear between June and the end of this
year, taking the total to more than 450,000.
Sir Brian joined civil engineers, architects and surveyors in London to
launch a 'battle bus' to travel to the Conservative conference.
Industry leaders will beg ministers not to cut money for construction in the
autumn public-spending round. They also want a cut in interest rates and
measures to help the housing market such as higher thresholds for mortgage
tax relief and the scrapping of stamp duty.
'We look to the chancellor's Autumn Statement to sustain public investment
in vital capital building programmes,' said Sir Brian. 'Instead, we read
increasingly of the threat of cuts to our capital spending programmes. So we
are now intensifying our lobbying efforts.'
A survey published yesterday by the confederation shows a further
deterioration in building industry workloads and will increase pressure on
the government.
It shows that confidence over future workloads has slipped even further,
with an increasing number of firms planning to shed workers in the next few
months. A fifth of companies questioned were working at less than half
capacity. The number of new inquiries for work was at its lowest level since
last year.
The survey was conducted in September among 600 of the confederation's 7,000
member companies. Ucatt, the construction union, warned yesterday that the
number of jobs lost in the industry might rise to 500,000 if the government
cut its Pounds 2bn housing budget.
