<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Banks defend actions on Pounds deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CLEARING banks hit back yesterday against allegations from politicians
that they have made huge speculative profits out of sterling's withdrawal
from the European exchange rate mechanism.
Mr Peter Wood, finance director of Barclays Bank - speaking for all UK
clearing banks - said Bank of England regulations made it impossible that
any of them could have made enormous profits from trading in sterling on
September 16 when the currency was taken out of the ERM.
'We have limits on the open positions we can run,' he said. The limits were
partly banks' internal constraints; partly Bank of England restrictions.
As a result, even had the banks been convinced that sterling would fall
sharply below its ERM floor - as it did on September 16 - they were unable
to carry a big negative position. When a bank has a negative position, it
has sold currency that it does not have.
Mr Wood said the big profits from selling the pound were made by investment
banks, some of which are not regulated by the Bank of England; fund
management groups; and companies' treasury departments.
'On the Wednesday we at Barclays bought almost exactly Pounds 1bn from
non-banks (investment banks and fund managers),' he said. 'That is two or
three times the amount we would typically buy from these institutions.' Mr
Wood admitted that the clearing banks made good profits from trading in
sterling on the day, although Barclays' profit was significantly less than
Pounds 100m.
He said the bulk of profits derived from marketmaking by taking a dealing
turn, rather than by taking a speculative position. In other words, it was
the volume of trading in the market that benefited the banks most, rather
than the direction of sterling's price.
The British Bankers' Association said the banks had been stung into
defending their behaviour in the foreign markets by politicians' allegations
that they had made vast windfall profits. They were particularly concerned
at the suggestion by Lord Callaghan, the former Labour prime minister, that
there should be a special windfall tax on banks' dealing profits.
</TEXT>
