<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Kiss-me-quick gives way to the stiff upper lip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEVER underestimate the dogged loyalty of the Conservative party's poor
bloody infantry. Four election victories on, after all, most of those
travelling to Brighton had expected this year's conference to be a riotous
celebration.
But on the prom yesterday, kiss-me-quick hats had given way to stiff upper
lips, braced against an equally stiff southerly wind, choppy waters in the
stock market and the news that sterling had plunged yet a further few
pfennigs. It seems triumphalism has made way for a mood more akin to the
Dunkirk spirit.
Asked who to blame for the continuing recession, Mr Grenville Horsfall, a
dour-faced manager from Halifax's 'amusement industry', was in no doubt.
'It's the Bundesbank,' he said, definitively absolving our embattled
chancellor and blaming it on the Germans.
Mr Norman Lamont, he insisted, could not be held responsible for the
policies of Mr Helmut Kohl, the German leader, adding for comfort's sake
that in the long term the downturn would be 'a mere blip on the screen'.
And how was West Yorkshire bearing up? 'Well, they couldn't be any more
against us than they were at the election,' butted in a companion, clearly
trying to be helpful: 'And we didn't do too badly then.'
All around the barricades of the Grand Hotel, a thin blue line of Sussex's
finest stared out to sea, ready for most eventualities short of a full-blown
invasion. Outside brave faces and robust sentiments were the order of the
day.
A retired test pilot and his wife from Northern Ireland were ready to pay
for their patriotism from their pocketbooks.
'I was skiing in France this year with the pound at FFr11, next year it will
be FFr8,' the pilot said. 'I think they should raise taxes to give a message
to people that we are serious.'
However, what was less clear among a random sample of representatives - as
Conservatives at the conference are called - was what exactly the grassroots
want the leadership to show it is serious about.
There was a surprisingly clear message of support for the chancellor with
representatives unanimously rejecting the calls for his resignation and
emphasising that he had only been acting under prime ministerial orders when
he devalued the pound. But views differed strongly over Britain's future
relationship with the European Community.
In spite of Mr John Major's insistence that the Maastricht treaty must be
ratified, many argued for caution. And there was scepticism bordering on
outright opposition about any return to the European exchange rate
mechanism.
Mr Jerry Froggett, a 21-year-old Leeds history student, was typical of many
when he argued that Britain should be 'at the heart of Europe' while at the
same time staying out of the ERM and rewriting the Maastricht treaty.
Councillor David Bradbury of Dulwich, south London, a 30-year-old civil
servant dressed in the tweed and brogues beloved by young fogeys, argued
similarly that the prime minister should take the ratification of the treaty
'slower rather than faster'.
'Denmark must be accommodated,' he stressed, observing apparently without
ironic intent that the party was less ill at ease than during the challenge
to the leadership of the then Mrs Margaret Thatcher.
Mr Phil McCullough, a retired Jaguar salesman from Hackney, east London,
disagreed at least about Denmark. While emphasising that 'drastic decisions'
had to be made, he counselled that the prime minister should proceed
cautiously and ratify the treaty.
'There is a lot of support for Major,' he insisted, adding almost as an
afterthought. 'The consensus is: we would not like to be in his shoes.'
</TEXT>
