FT  06 OCT 92 / Sceptics warm to Euro showdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY Euro-sceptics were openly relishing the prospect of a head-on
confrontation with the party leadership yesterday as they put the final
touches to their tactics for rallying support among grassroots activists
during the conference.
Rebel MPs held a private meeting in the afternoon to plan their strategy for
the conference debates proper and for the fringe.
Mr John Major, however, used his speech to the annual eve-of-conference
dinner for Tory party agents to reaffirm his own commitment to the
Maastricht treaty.
The prime minister told them that his aim was for a European Community run
in British interests, and warned that abandoning the agreement would mean no
British government was ever taken seriously again in EC negotiations.
Evidence of dissent was again apparent with the publication of several
emergency amendments to conference motions on Europe and the economy, urging
that the Maastricht treaty should not be ratified and that sterling should
not rejoin the European exchange rate mechanism.
The amendments are unlikely to be voted on, but organisers promised that the
full range of opinion would be reflected in discussion.
Sir Norman Fowler, party chairman, said 'every worthwhile facet of debate'
would be expressed. In a signal that the leadership wants to play down the
fringe meetings, at which former cabinet ministers are expected to be among
those challenging government policy, he added: 'The major action at this
conference will not be at fringe meetings, it will be at the conference
itself.'
Looking beyond the conference, the most outspoken Euro-sceptics predicted
that if Mr Major proceeded with the Maastricht bill it might prove to be his
downfall, with one hinting that revolt might spread to other issues.
Equating such a move with 'opening up the Russian front', Mr Tony Marlow
said the only way Mr Major could secure the bill would be by a coalition
with the Labour party.
