FT  06 OCT 92 / Shop assistants sue over Sunday trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BATTLE over Sunday trading in England and Wales returned to the High
Court yesterday when four women shop assistants employed by B&amp;Q sued
Kirklees Council in West Yorkshire for lost wages resulting from the
enforced Sunday closure of the DIY chain's Dewsbury store over a four-month
period last year.
The case was adjourned until next month together with a renewed application
by Kirklees for injunctions preventing B&amp;Q and Comet, the retail chain, from
opening stores in its area on Sundays.
Mr Nicholas Davidson, counsel for B&amp;Q and Comet, said the length of the case
would depend on whether the European Court of Justice gave its long-awaited
judgment on the legality of the Sunday trading laws in the meantime.
The European court has been asked by the House of Lords to rule on whether
restrictions on Sunday trading in England and Wales under the 1950 Shops Act
clash with EC provisions on free trade.
