<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Plunging markets test Major: Steep fall in equities Sterling
plumbs new depths Interest rate fears intensify
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRIGHTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night faced a crisis of confidence in London's financial
markets after a slump in share prices and a sliding pound raised intense
pressure for a clear statement of the government's economic strategy.
As the markets cast a shadow over the opening today of the Conservative
party conference, Mr Major responded to crumbling confidence by stressing
that low inflation remained the 'centrepiece' of his policy.
But share prices had already suffered their biggest one-day fall for five
years, prompting Lord Tebbit, a former Conservative party chairman, to warn
that Britain now faced 'an economic and political crisis'.
Arriving in Brighton, the prime minister told journalists that sterling,
which yesterday fell to another record low against the D-Mark, had been
caught in the much wider turbulence on financial markets across Europe. The
pound had been particularly hit only because it was one of the world's most
widely traded currencies. He added: 'These things happen from time to time.
. . .I don't think people should get unduly panicked about it.'
But as Mr Michael Heseltine's budget at the Department of Trade and Industry
emerged as the latest victim of Treasury spending cuts, Mr Major said he
would not shirk 'difficult choices' over public spending.
The economic gloom was deepened by a warning from the Building Employers'
Confederation of further big job losses.
Throwing a pall over what had already promised to be a fractious party
conference, the London stock market recorded its biggest one-day fall since
the 1987 crash. The FT-SE 100 share index lost 103.4 to 2,446.3, amid
concern about the apparent lack of direction to UK economic policy.
The policy vacuum saw the pound lose fall 3 3/4 pfennigs in London to
DM2.3925, bringing losses to 12 1/2 pfennigs in three trading days. It is
more than 55 pfennigs below its former ERM central rate of DM2.95. In New
York, the pound closed at DM2.43165.
But as sterling's weakness intensified concerns among senior Conservatives
that the government might soon be forced to raise interest rates, Mr Major
declined to anticipate Mr Norman Lamont's speech to the conference on
Thursday.
He told journalists: 'I am not going to pre-empt what the chancellor is to
say. But we have made it perfectly clear that the centrepiece of our
economic policy remains to get inflation low and to keep inflation low.'
Mr Lamont faces growing City pressure to use what was originally envisaged
as a general description of economic objectives to issue a more detailed
statement of how policy will operate outside the ERM.
Senior ministers were still stressing yesterday that the party conference
did not provide the right venue for a technical analysis of the operation of
monetary policy. But they acknowledged that unless Mr Lamont offered a clear
set of guidelines on Thursday, the markets might force a damaging rise in
interest rates.
Speaking at a private dinner for party officials last night, Mr Major
acknowledged that sterling's ignominious departure from the ERM had left his
gov-ernment under fire. But in what senior Tory officials characterised as a
'fighting speech', he indicated that he was ready to spell out the 'home
truths' on which economic policy would be based.
He sought also to pre-empt the threat of a damaging battle over Europe by
stressing from the outset of the conference that he would not be budged from
his support for the Maastricht treaty.
Confirming that the Maastricht bill would be brought back to the House of
Commons later this month, Mr Major said: 'I have no intention of going back
to Europe to break my word and the agreement I entered into.'
Sir Norman Fowler will attempt to reinforce the call for unity when the
conference opens this morning with a warning to delegates that the
Conservatives have built their election victories by eschewing public
divisions.
But leading Tory Eurosceptics signalled that they planned to use today's
debate on the government's European policy to demonstrate the strength of
opposition to Maastricht.
