<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 92 / Workers' rights to be tested in court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CHALLENGE to the government's interpretation of a European Community
directive on workers' employment rights after takeovers begins in the High
Court today.
Natfhe, the lecturers' union, says the law should be changed to prevent
organisations that acquire public-sector bodies from dismissing workers or
imposing inferior pay and conditions. The union says UK law breaches the
directive, as the law does not require employers to honour the employment
contracts they inherit when acquiring non-profit-making organisations.
Contracts must be honoured when one organisation takes over another in the
private sector, and Natfhe argues that the rules should protect all workers.
The government - under pressure from the European Commission - has agreed to
add an amendment to its planned employment bill, due in the next
parliamentary session, to extend equal protection to all workers. The
Commission is also preparing to take the British government to the European
Court of Justice.
Natfhe is continuing with the judicial review proceedings, which affect
50,000 lecturers in polytechnics, because Employment Department officials
are unable to announce the changes publicly before parliament debates them.
The lecturers will face new employers next year when polytechnics move out
of local-authority control in their switch to independent college
corporations.
The Local Government Management Board calculates that councils have lost
almost 20,000 jobs since 1987 as a result of compulsory competitive
tendering. A further 2,000 are expected to be removed from direct employment
by March next year Many workers have been re-hired by private contractors on
worse terms and conditions.
The EC Commission has argued for five years that the UK rules breach the
directive. Natfhe will also argue that employers must consult workers'
representatives before any transfer of ownership.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
