<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 92 / Private bank to be closed down
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England announced last night that it is to wind up the
operations of Mount Banking Corporation, a privately owned London-based
bank.
The Bank said it had won court approval to put in provisional liquidators.
Mr Philip Wallace and Mr Timothy Hayward of KPMG Peat Marwick were sent in
yesterday.
'The basis of our petition was that there were just and equitable grounds
for winding up the bank,' the Bank of England said. It stressed that it 'did
not allege insolvency'.
Mount Banking Corporation had a total balance sheet value of Pounds 200m at
the end of March this year. Its 3,000 depositors, who have deposits of about
Pounds 160m, are mainly Asians resident in India and East Africa, and
according to the Bank it has only a few depositors in the UK.
The company has a subsidiary in the Cayman Islands and affiliated companies
in Kenya and India.
Mount Banking Corporation is only the second bank to be moved on by the Bank
since it closed Bank of Credit and Commerce International in July last year.
The other was National Guardian Mortgage in Surrey, put into administration
in March this year owing 1,000 depositors about Pounds 10m.
</TEXT>
