<DATELINE>
   GEORGETOWN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GUYANA'S presidential election gets under way today, placing the future of
the country's major bauxite and sugar industries in the hands of the 385,000
registered voters, writes Canute James in Georgetown.
The two long-time rivals contesting the presidency hold opposing views on
the economy, particularly the divestment of state-owned economic
enterprises.
The People's National Congress, led by Mr Desmond Hoyte, the president, says
it will continue its four-year-old divestment programme which plans to sell
the economically important sugar industry.
Dr Cheddi Jagan, leader of the main opposition People's Progressive party,
has said the divestment of all state companies by the PNC administration
will be reviewed if he wins the election.
Dr Jagan says a PPP administration will have no obligation to any earlier
divestment agreements.
