<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 92 / Cost of residential care 'forcing old to sell homes'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RISING cost of long-term residential care is forcing the elderly to sell
their homes, according to a report published today by the Family Policy
Studies Centre, an independent research body.
But even the sale of a house will be insufficient to pay for more than five
years in a private nursing home on average, according to the report,
sponsored by Help the Aged.
An average house, realising around Pounds 66,000, would pay for eight years
in private residential care without nursing.
That would mean an increased burden on the families of the elderly in care,
which the report estimates at between Pounds 30 and Pounds 40 a week. Social
security would also need to pay more, and the report estimates the cost to
the taxpayer of supporting elderly people in private care at close to Pounds
2bn this year.
Elderly people are the main consumers of health services, with those aged 85
and over costing the National Health Service and community services an
average of five times as much as those aged between five and 64, according
to Mr Francis McGlone, author of the report.
The FSPC study adds to a report by Nuffield College, Oxford, published this
year, which estimated that houses to the value of Pounds 2.5bn were sold
each year to pay for long-term care.
According to the Nuffield report, nearly two thirds of those who owned their
homes when they went into long-term care needed to sell them to pay the
bills.
Over the past year, several large insurance companies, including Commercial
Union, Eagle Star and Private Patients Plan, have launched insurance
policies aimed at paying for long-term care.
A wide-ranging public debate is needed to establish the extent to which
families should take responsibility for dependent relatives, a report says
today, Alan Pike writes.
The report, by Professor Anthea Tinker and colleagues at the Age Concern
Institute of Gerontology at King's College, London, says examination of the
extent of the state's responsibility for care of the elderly should be
informed by overseas experience, including the German system where adult
sons and daughters had some legal responsibility for dependent parents.
About 6m people in Britain care for dependents. The report says carers risk
having low incomes in retirement because of lost employment opportunities.
Disability and Dependency in Old Age.  Family Policy Studies Centre, 231
Baker Street, London NW1.  Pounds 7.95.  Carnegie Inquiry into the Third Age
Report Six.  Bailey Management Services, 127 Sandgate Road, Folkestone, Kent
CT20 2BL.  Pounds 9.50.
Letters, Page 15
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
