<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 92 / Abolition of wages councils urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOLITION of the remaining wages councils and privatisation of the
government conciliation service Acas are being urged on the eve of the
Conservative Party conference by the Institute of Direct-ors.
The government said earlier this year it saw no 'permanent place' for wages
councils, which at present set minimum rates for about 10 per cent of the
working population. There has been speculation that their abolition would be
included in this autumn's employment bill.
Some campaigners against abolition believe that Mrs Gillian Shephard, the
employment secretary, will announce the winding up of the councils at the
Conservative conference this week.
The belief is based partly on a hostile response from the Department of
Employment to a recent letter from the Equal Opportunities Commission urging
retention of the councils in the interests of women, who make up nearly 2m
of the 2.5m people covered by the councils. The department pointed out that
most of the low-paid live in households with other incomes and are not poor.
The Trades Union Congress will be lobbying delegates to the Conservative
conference in Brighton today. The TUC argues that abolition of the wages
councils will push thousands of people below the poverty line and points to
a recent NOP survey which found that nine out of 10 people support
protection for people on low pay.
Supporting abolition of the 26 remaining wages councils - mainly covering
service industries such as hotels and restaurants - the IoD argues that the
councils, far from protecting workers, constitute a bureaucratic
intervention in the labour market that is especially onerous on businesses
employing fewer than 50 people.
The IoD is also calling for the abolition of the licensing of employment
agencies and for measures to ensure equal tax treatment of employees and the
self-employed. The present system of licensing employment agencies, the IoD
says, does not appear to provide any genuine protection for those using
them, but the cost of compliance imposes an excessive burden on business.
'These measures will encourage labour market flexibility and contribute to
British industry's recovery from recession,' said Dr Ann Robinson, head of
the IoD policy unit.
</TEXT>
