<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 92 / Major ready to postpone debate on ERM reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR has signalled he is ready to shelve debate on Britain's demand
for reform of the European exchange rate mechanism until after this month's
emergency summit in Birmingham.
The prime minister's stance, set out in a confidential letter sent to fellow
EC leaders, reflects his acceptance of other governments' fears that public
discussion of changes might add to the mechanism's present strains.
The emergence of Mr Major's letter coincided yesterday with a determined
ministerial campaign to prevent this week's Conservative conference from
degenerating into a civil war over the Maastricht treaty.
In an interview with the FT, Sir Norman Fowler, the party chairman, warned
opponents of Maastricht in the Tory party that Mr Major and his entire
cabinet will 'come out fighting' to ensure that it gets through the House of
Commons. That message will be repeated throughout the week by a succession
of cabinet ministers.
But a warning by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, that sterling's
recent slide could not be allowed to continue indefinitely reinforced fears
among nervous Tory MPs that Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, could be
forced to raise interest rates.
Mr Lamont, who is preparing for a crucial speech to the party conference on
Thursday, has said he would if necessary reverse the one percentage point
cut which followed sterling's departure from the ERM. But an increase now
could undermine fatally his position in the cabinet.
Mr Clarke was echoed by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary,
in a reminder to party activists who gather in Brighton tomorrow that the
pound's devaluation will mean tougher controls on public spending. Alongside
sharp cutbacks already agreed in capital spending on transport, schools,
hospital and prison building, the Treasury now wants a cash reduction in the
health service budget and a freeze in some social security benefits.
As some ministers call for a public sector pay freeze rather than further
reductions in capital programmes, Mr Lamont is expected to chair another
meeting of the cabinet's public spending committee later today.
Mr Heseltine, however, sought to dispel suggestions that the government is
considering raising income tax to reduce a public sector deficit forecast at
more than Pounds 40bn next year. In private, ministers will not rule out an
extension of value added tax to areas such as domestic fuel and newspapers,
but Mr Heseltine described the option of higher taxes as 'the least
attractive to a Conservative government'.
Mr Major's acknowledgment that there can be no immediate changes in the ERM
came in the letter sent out to his European counterparts at the end of last
week. In his role as the current EC president, he had wanted finance
ministers to review the ERM's working at the Birmingham summit on October
16.
But the letter said he now accepted that several other governments objected
to the attendance of finance ministers.
Instead the summit would discuss generally the recent turbulence on the
financial markets based on an interim report by the Community's monetary
committee.
But most of the leaders' attention will be devoted to drafting a proposed
declaration to give substance to the principle of subsidiarity  - the
decentralisation of decision-making in the EC.
Mr Major believes there is much greater impetus behind his demand for repair
of the 'fault-lines' in the ERM than is publicly acknowledged by many
governments.
But the prime minister acknowledges that those governments whose currencies
have been under speculative attack, including France, cannot afford to admit
publicly that the mechanism is fundamentally flawed.
The pressures on Mr Major were highlighted yesterday by two opinion polls on
his performance as premier.
The 33 per cent satisfaction rating found by Mori for The Sunday Times, and
the 34 per cent satisfaction rating according to Gallup in The Sunday
Telegraph are both sharply down on Mr Major's previous scores. A further
Mori poll for The Times today suggests 68 per cent would have voted against
ratification of the Maastricht treaty if a referendum were held.
