<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 92 / Ministers query cost of trade groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE prospect of streamlining the hundreds of trade associations in the UK to
bring greater efficiency into industrial lobbying is being raised by
ministers at the Department of Trade and Industry, concerned that the
plethora of organisations could be hindering business's competitiveness.
In informal meetings with industrialists and businessmen, Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, and Mr Tim Sainsbury, the industry
minister, have been asking whether companies are getting value for money
from their membership of a range of associations.
The ministers are conscious that even medium-sized businesses may spend
several thousand pounds each year on membership of as many as 20 trade
associations.
Most trade associations employ a levy formula based on a percentage of the
member company's payroll or turnover, or both.
The Chemical Industries Association, for example, charges its 220 members
using a formula based on turnover and the actual number of employees. The
CIA has a turnover of Pounds 4.2m a year and the minimum charge is Pounds
3,650.
The Association of the British Pharmaceutical Industry has 100 members
charged Pounds 14,000 to Pounds 180,000 a year.
While the DTI emphasises that the future of trade associations must be for
industry to decide, in making it clear which organisations they take
seriously, Mr Heseltine and his colleagues have a powerful way of putting
pressure on those they see as less valuable.
The dual pressures on associations - declining income combined with
increasing costs as they have to operate in Brussels as well as at
Westminster - are seen by ministers as providing an opportunity for industry
to ensure it is getting a good deal.
One example of the sort of changes which could come about was seen at the
start of this month, when a number of organisations in the clothing and
textile industries joined forces to strengthen their lobbying power by
forming the British Apparel and Textiles Confederation.
</TEXT>
