<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Norfolk is one of those few remaining corners of England which still feels
more than a touch primitive. No surprise, then, to learn from C4's Animal
Squad Undercover (9.00) that among the yokels there are still avid followers
of cock-fighting. (How much worse cock-fighting is than, say, factory
farming chickens is a moot point.) The opening part of this trilogy follows
the RSPCA's undercover squad in its dogged but ultimately frustrated effort
to see justice done to the cock-fighters.
BBC 2's Out of Darkness (7.50), the consistently interesting series on the
troubles of African states, tonight reaches the Cameroons, whose footballers
with their wonderful pelvic-thrusting dances provided quite the most
memorable moments of the last World Cup - not excepting Gazza's blubbing.
C4's late-night theme is a highly praised Mexican historical epic, Cabeza de
Vaca (12.00), based on the memoirs of an eponymous 16th-century conquistador
in Florida. Captured by an Indian tribe, de Vaca is brought to realise that
the Indians' moral code is superior to that of the Spaniards.
</TEXT>
