<HEADLINE>
FT  05 OCT 92 / Pressure builds on Craxi as son leaves politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Vittorio 'Bobo' Craxi, the son of Italy's Socialist party leader, Mr
Bettino Craxi, is withdrawing from politics after a series of allegations
and setbacks in the wake of the Milan political corruption scandal.
The younger Mr Craxi, a leading member of the Socialist party organisation
in Italy's second city, seemed set until recently to follow in his father's
footsteps, possibly to the top of the party developed by his father into a
linchpin of recent coalition governments.
Pressure is also building up on Mr Craxi senior to step down as party
leader.
Last week he attacked Mr Claudio Martelli, the justice minister and his
heir-apparent, for 'disloyalty' for his increasing calls for change in the
party.
The Socialists, and the Craxis in particular, have been tainted by the
growing revelations of political corruption in big Italian cities.
Milan has been a traditional Socialist stronghold and remains the powerbase
for the Craxi family. Mr Bettino Craxi's sister is married to Mr Paolo
Pillitteri, the previous Socialist mayor of Milan, who is one of a group of
MPs now under investigation for alleged fraud and receiving kickbacks.
Though no charges have been brought against Mr 'Bobo' Craxi, he has
complained of being regularly insulted by strangers and of being taken for
guilty when actually innocent.
Revelations of political corruption have been mushrooming following the
discovery last week of a fraud in the Abruzzo region in southern Italy
leading to the arrest of seven of the 11 members of the regional
administration.
Meanwhile, the Christian Democrats, Italy's biggest political party, named
Mr Mino Martinazzoli as their next leader to replace Mr Arnaldo Forlani.
Mr Forlani was one of the triumvirate of powerbrokers along with Mr Craxi
and Mr Giulio Andreotti, the former prime minister, in the previous
coalition government.
Mr Martinazzoli will be formally appointed at the party's next congress, due
later this month.
Senior party members welcomed his appointment as a symbol of the change
needed for the party to regain electoral support. In local elections in the
northern province of Mantua last week, the Christian Democrats' share of the
vote dropped by over a third.
The Christian Democrats lost ground in northern Italy in last April's
general elections.
</TEXT>
