<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FALL in sterling as hopes of interest rate cuts in Germany and the US
evaporated depressed derivatives markets yesterday, although trading
activity was at a low ebb, writes Terry Byland.
In stock index futures, the December contract on the Footsie lost much of
its fair value premium on this week and also for the new equity account
which opens on Monday; fair value is the premium against the cash market
after allowing for dividend flows and financing costs on the underlying
stocks.
The December contract had an erratic session, opening lower and then moving
higher, only to turn sharply downwards at the end of the day. At its best
level of around 2,636, the contract could not match the best of the previous
day.
In after hours dealings, the contract traded around 2,575, a premium of 26
to cash and at a discount of around nine on next week's estimated fair value
of 35. Total volume was extremely low at 9,827
Traded options was steadier, at 35,791, with the FT-SE contract trading
9,046 contracts and Trafalgar House (3,272) also active. Glaxo headed the
list of stock options.
