FT  03 OCT 92 / International Company News: USAir union threatens strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE THREAT of industrial action loomed over USAir, the US carrier in which
British Airways is seeking to invest Dollars 750m in return for a large
minority stake, after the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers said its members appeared to have voted in favour of a
strike.
The announcement from the IAM came late yesterday afternoon. The union -
representative for over 8,000 mechanics and related workers at the airline -
acknowledged that a few smaller 'locals' (branches) were still left to vote
today. But it said results so far suggested a 'nearly unanimous vote' for
strike action.
The union added that it would set a strike date within 72 hours. 'The IAM
takes no pleasure in announcing strike plans,' said Mr John Peterpaul, IAM
transportation vice president, 'but USAir must understand our members feel
they have no choice but to stand up to company demands that would force IAM
members to carry a heavier burden than other employee groups'. He said the
union was willing to resume negotiations but no talks have been scheduled.
The strike threat comes after a contract offer from USAir which the union
claims would mean permanent wage cuts and work rule concessions. Yesterday,
the union was sharply critical of British Airways, suggesting the UK carrier
had 'imposed its heavy hand in USAir matters', even though its proposed
investment has get to gain regulatory approval.
The IAM said it was withdrawing support for the proposed link between the
two airlines. BA declined to comment.
