FT  03 OCT 92 / Letter: Palindrome fever heightens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr CYRIL SANGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Mr Apsion's palindromes (Letters, September 26) result from the
illogical way dates are usually written: day/month/year. His American
friends, who use an even less sensible method (month/day/year), will
encounter the first of their remaining seven 5-figure palindrome dates of
the millennium on March 3 1993 and the rest at 13-month intervals,
celebrating jointly with him on September 9 1999. The logical format is:
year/month/day. Papers so marked may be arranged chronologically by sorting
them in numerical order. I look forward to saluting with Mr Apsion the
palindrome date 921129 (or 29.11.92).
Dr Cyril Sanger,
317 Lydecker Street,
Englewood,
New Jersey
